    <!-- Application Structure Plan: The application uses a thematic, section-based structure, grouping tenses into Present, Past, and Future categories. This is a standard and intuitive pedagogical approach. A sticky navigation bar allows for quick scrolling. Each tense is presented on an interactive card with internal tabs for "Rules," "Usage & Signals," "Examples," and "Trainer." This design breaks down complex information into digestible, user-controlled chunks, promoting active learning over passive reading and preventing information overload, which is superior to a static table for this type of content. -->
    <!-- Visualization & Content Choices: Goal: Organize, Inform & Engage. Method: Structured HTML/CSS with Tailwind for a card-based layout and interactive forms. Interaction: Clickable tabs within each card switch between content panes (Rules, Usage, Examples, Trainer). The Trainer tab contains multiple-choice questions with dynamic feedback and score tracking. Justification: Since the source data is textual and rule-based, traditional charts are inappropriate. The interactive card/tab model is the most effective way to organize this layered information, allowing users to drill down into specifics as needed. The addition of interactive exercises directly addresses the need for practical application of grammar rules. Library/Method: Vanilla JS for interactions and exercise logic. CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used. -->
    <!-- CONFIRMATION: NO SVG graphics used. NO Mermaid JS used. -->
